The paper focuses on Natural Language Processing (NLP) techniques applied to cybersecurity texts, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.CL (Computation and Language) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with the challenge of sparse texts, which is a common issue in the cybersecurity domain, indicating that it could also belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. The paper proposes a novel algorithm to incorporate diverse types of text annotations in word embedding, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The paper also evaluates its method on two cybersecurity text corpora, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the task of Named Entity Recognition, Syntactic Parsing, and Sentiment Analysis, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) sub-category.
